<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1934-03-15T14:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1934-03-15T14:00:00-05:00" n="479" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d479">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">251.11 Insull, Samuel/365:
                                Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in Greece</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">MacVeagh</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Athens</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-03-15T21:00:00+02:00">March 15, 1934—9
                                        p.m.</date><lb/>[Received March 15—7:08 p.m.]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>32. The Foreign Minister has just telephoned me that Insull has
                                disappeared. He further stated his belief that the fugitive must be
                                hiding in Athens but I have telegraphed Belgrade, Tirana, Sofia,
                                Istanbul, Bucharest, Cairo, Beirut, Borne, Jerusalem, Baghdad and
                                Teheran. Mrs. Insull is here.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">MacVeagh</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>